<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Lord_Konradt on 12-26-1999 03:28 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I was wondering what everybodies opinion is about party in Project C or not.

Personally I like it when there is no party, This way you have more bonding with your alter-ego. And it makes Realtime gameplay more pleasant, and less complex. The other advantage is that in multiplayer, you could have your own character to relate to. And maybe make it possible to keep your character in both multiplayer, and single-player. I know this could make the game imbalanced, because you can start a game with a super hero, but this could be fixed, by making the difficulty of the game, biased towards the level of the character. (just a thought that pop'ed in my head).
Not having a personnal character was actually one of the things I did not like in Baldur's Gate ( and other RPG's), was that you could  not really do this. You could make a blue print of your character, but that felt so fake. But the worst thing was the joint inventory. That was sooo bad. Our first(and our last) multiplayer was completely ruined by this. Because of the joint inventory, One person could spend all the money, without consent. I know that there was an alternative, but this I found was even worse. I could imagine the quarrels one could have of who, would be this leader.

So What I mean is ...
I like it the most when there is only a party in multiplayer (it would be difficult if there wasn't :-) ). And that you have nearly complete control over that character, and his belongings.

I hope you understood anything about this ranting :-).


------------------
Greetz,
Lord Konradt.

</TEXTAREA>
